        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe the CO(3-2) line and simultaneously obtain continuum emission at band 7. We chose the correlator mode with a 1.875 GHz bandwidth in the frequency domain mode and use four spectral windows in four basebands to maximize the continuum sensitivity with the total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to study the spatial distribution of molecular gas and dust, we use the spatial resolution of 1 arcsec (~170 pc scale). We will compare the properties of the GRB site with other regions in the host galaxy. We use 7 pointing mosaic with Nyquist sampling to cover the host galaxy. Because the aim of this proposal is to detect molecular gas and dust around the GRB site, at star-forming regions, and at the galaxy center, and we do not need the ACA. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimate the required sensitivity for the CO(3--2) line by using the relation of surface density between SFR and gas (Schmidt-Kennicutt relation; Kennicutt 1998). Because the SFR (or IR luminosity) of the GRB site has not been derived in previous studies, we calculate the sensitivity based on the information on the WR region, a star-forming region close to the GRB site. The SFR is 0.02 Mun/yr in the WR region, where the diameter of the region is approximately between 2"-3". The SFR surface density is ~0.1 Msun/yr/kpc^2. By using the Schmidt-Kennicutt relation, the estimated velocity-integrated CO(3-2) intensity for the proposed synthesized beam (1") is 5.1 K km/s. Here we use a Galactic CO(3-2)/CO(1-0) line ratio of 0.27 (Carilli &amp; Walter 2013). In order to obtain a deep constraint on the GRB site, we aim to achieve a factor of five deeper noise level than estimated for the WR region. By assuming a CO line width of 68 km/s, a median value for local dwarf galaxies (Leroy et al. 2005), the requested sensitivity for detecting the CO line with SN &gt;= 5 is 2.8 mK, which corresponds to 0.27 mJy with a velocity resolution of 35 km/s. 

The 5sigma detection limit for continuum achieved in the observations is 0.02 mJy/beam with a 7.5~GHz bandwidth, which is enough to detect the dust continuum of the host galaxy or the WR region significantly (SN ~&gt; 10). </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
