    <prp:abstract>Long-duration gamma-ray bursts (GRBs) are thought to be associated with the explosions of massive stars and are accordingly expected to reside in star-forming regions with molecular gas. Multi-wavelength observations of GRB host galaxies have been conducted to understand the environment where GRBs occur. However, molecular gas observations are very limited. There is only one example with spatially resolved molecular gas and dust information, where the resolution of 4 kpc is not enough to resolve the local environment. 

We propose CO and dust continuum observations of the GRB980425 host, which is the nearest GRB (z=0.0085, 36.1 Mpc). This is the unique target because it is possible to identify precisely the GRB site, which is impossible in other hosts. The immediate objective is to reveal the spatial distribution of molecular gas, dust, and gas-to-dust ratio with a resolution of 1" (170 pc). We will examine the difference between the GRB site and other regions to examine the characteristic property of the environment where GRBs occur. 

(This is a resubmission of our project (2013.1.00650.S), which was approved as a highest priority project in cycle 2)</prp:abstract>
